Q: What is Reflection:
    - Reflection is used to inspect and manipulate classes, methods, and fields at runtime.
    - Also spring is used to Create objects, Inject dependencies, Read annotations
    - It is mainly used by frameworks like Spring, Hibernate, and JUnit for dependency injection, object creation,
      annotation processing, and dynamic method execution where class details are not known at compile time.
    - We use Reflection when we want Java programs to work dynamically, without knowing class details at compile time.
    - Also Reflection is called as backbone of frameworks.
    - Spring uses reflection to find classes, create objects, and connect them automatically without you using new.

    1) To Work with Unknown Classes at Runtime
    Example: String className = "com.app.service.UserService";
             Class<?> c = Class.forName(className);
             Object obj = c.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();

    - In this example we are just passing the Class Name as a string without doing the hard code for it.
    - In EmailService mail = new EmailService(); in this EmailService class send() methods only get execute if we have to call
      SmsService methods so we need to write more code for it so based on runtime it is decided by the reflection.

    2) Testing Frameworks (JUnit)

    3) Accessing Private Members (Controlled Use)

