Q: What is autoboxing and unboxing: Autoboxing and unboxing allow Java to automatically convert between primitive types and their wrapper class objects.

    Autoboxing means:
    - Java automatically converts a primitive type into its wrapper class object.
    Example: int a = 10;
             Integer b = a;   // autoboxing
    - Integer b = Integer.valueOf(a);

    Unboxing means:
    - Java automatically converts a wrapper class object into a primitive type.
    Example: Integer x = 20;
             int y = x;   // unboxing
    - int y = x.intValue();

- What is needs of it: Because collections work only with objects, not primitives.
    ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
    list.add(5);   // autoboxing (int → Integer)

