    Q: What goes in Stack? (STACK MEMORY)
        - Local variables
        - Method calls
        - Method parameters
        - References to objects

    Key points
        - Fast
        - Thread-safe
        - Memory is freed automatically
        - Works in LIFO (Last In First Out)

    Example:
        void test() {
            int x = 10;      // stack
            User u = new User(); // reference u is in stack
        }

    Q: What goes in Heap? (HEAP MEMORY)
        - Objects
        - Instance variables
        - Arrays

    Key points
        - Shared
        - Managed by Garbage Collector
        - Slower than stack

    Example:
        User u = new User();

Stack vs Heap:
    | Stack              | Heap            |
    | ------------------ | --------------- |
    | Stores method data | Stores objects  |
    | Faster             | Slower          |
    | Auto cleanup       | GC cleanup      |
    | Thread safe        | Not thread safe |

    ****

        Static Keywords:
        - Belongs to class, not object
        - Stored in Method Area (part of heap)

