String Pool:
    - String Pool (String Constant Pool) is a special memory area inside the Heap where Java stores unique string literals.
    - String pool is a JVM optimization where identical string literals are stored once and reused to save memory and improve performance.
    - Same string value → only ONE object in pool

    String a = "Hello";
    String b = new String("Hello");

    System.out.println(a == b);      // false
    System.out.println(a.equals(b)); // true

Transient: The transient keyword prevents a variable from being serialized.
    - To protect sensitive or temporary data (passwords, tokens, cache.
    - Example: transient String password; (it will not save this field in the memory)

Volatile: Ensures a variable’s value is always visible to all threads.
    - Why because to avoid stale/cached values in multithreading
    - Example: volatile boolean running; (Always read the latest value / means dont cache me)

